What you need to know:

The farmer has five sugar apple, 13 atemoya, eight soursop (graviola) , 14 custard apple and five jackfruit trees.He sourced the seedlings from Kenya Agricultural Research and Livestock Organisation, Embu, with each going at between Sh200 and Sh300 each.Soursop fruits, according to him, have several nutritional benefits that include keeping cancer at bay, improving eye health, relieving arthritis and help in maintaining good health of liver and kidney.He intends to add many rarer fruits like Kiwano, Durian and Mangosteen on his farm to provide different tastes, nutrients and varieties to the local market.